docs.abstract: How a lawn sign inspired by mom décor became a liberal mantra — and a symbol of a political battle over white womanhood.
docs.snippet: How a lawn sign inspired by mom décor became a liberal mantra — and a symbol of a political battle over white womanhood.
docs.lead_paragraph: There is a sign that has become ubiquitous on the lawns of Democrats who have lawns. “In This House, We Believe,” the sign begins, followed by a stack of progressive maxims listed in capital letters. The classic version reads: “Black Lives Matter / Women’s Rights Are Human Rights / No Human Is Illegal / Science Is Real / Love Is Love.” Then the kicker: “Kindness Is Everything.”

headline.main: ‘In This House’ Yard Signs, and Their Curious Power
headline.print_headline: The Curious, Persistent Power  Of a Yard Sign That Went Viral

docs.abstract: Whether the three men accused in Mr. Arbery’s death were motived by racism will quite likely be a major theme in the case.
docs.snippet: Whether the three men accused in Mr. Arbery’s death were motived by racism will quite likely be a major theme in the case.
docs.lead_paragraph: BRUNSWICK, Ga. — A complicated jury selection process kicked off Monday in the trial of the three white men accused of murdering Ahmaud Arbery, a Black man they had chased through a coastal Georgia neighborhood, with lawyers sparring over what kinds of questions the hundreds of potential jurors could be subjected to, including questions about their views on race and the Confederate battle flag.

headline.main: Jury Selection Begins in Trial Over Ahmaud Arbery’s Killing
headline.print_headline: Jury Selection Opens Trial in Arbery Killing

docs.abstract: A Black superintendent’s email to parents after the killing of George Floyd engulfed a small, predominantly white Maryland community in a yearlong firestorm.
docs.snippet: A Black superintendent’s email to parents after the killing of George Floyd engulfed a small, predominantly white Maryland community in a yearlong firestorm.
docs.lead_paragraph: CENTREVILLE, Md. — When Andrea Kane sat down to write a letter to parents in her school district days after George Floyd’s death in 2020, images of the Black man pleading for his life under the knee of a white Minnesota police officer were haunting her.

headline.main: Black Lives Matter, She Wrote. Then ‘Everything Just Imploded.’
headline.print_headline: After Note on Racism, School District ‘Imploded’

docs.abstract: Days before the election, Alvin Bragg, who is heavily favored to win office, is participating in an inquiry into Eric Garner’s killing by the N.Y.P.D.
docs.snippet: Days before the election, Alvin Bragg, who is heavily favored to win office, is participating in an inquiry into Eric Garner’s killing by the N.Y.P.D.
docs.lead_paragraph: It was the week before Election Day, but Alvin Bragg was not glad-handing or fund-raising, not out on the campaign trail or meeting with veterans of the office he hopes to run.

headline.main: Manhattan’s Likely Next D.A. Questions Police Over Eric Garner’s Death
headline.print_headline: He’s Likely Manhattan’s Next D.A., but Now Grills Police Over Garner’s Death

docs.abstract: “What really happened on that day?” Gwen Carr, Eric Garner’s mother, asked about her son’s death on Staten Island seven years ago.
docs.snippet: “What really happened on that day?” Gwen Carr, Eric Garner’s mother, asked about her son’s death on Staten Island seven years ago.
docs.lead_paragraph: The anguished pleas of Eric Garner as he struggled in a New York City police officer’s chokehold in 2014 galvanized millions, and his last words — “I can’t breathe,” repeated 11 times and captured on video — became a rallying cry for a protest movement demanding that police officers be held accountable.

headline.main: Officers to Testify About Eric Garner’s Death in Long-Delayed Inquiry
headline.print_headline: Police Officers to Testify  About Chokehold Death  In Long-Delayed Inquiry

docs.abstract: “Call and Response: The Story of Black Lives Matter” is a visually focused book by New York Times journalists that documents the transformative summer of 2020. Here’s how it came together.
docs.snippet: “Call and Response: The Story of Black Lives Matter” is a visually focused book by New York Times journalists that documents the transformative summer of 2020. Here’s how it came together.
docs.lead_paragraph: It was a daunting place to start: Thousands of photos. Hundreds of articles. Protests that stretched not only from coast to coast, but also around the world.

headline.main: Chronicling the Black Lives Matter Movement, for Kids
headline.print_headline: Finding a Protest’s Place in History

docs.abstract: Three white men are charged in the death of Mr. Arbery, a Black man, in a coastal Georgia suburb. Jury selection begins Monday.
docs.snippet: Three white men are charged in the death of Mr. Arbery, a Black man, in a coastal Georgia suburb. Jury selection begins Monday.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — The three white Georgia men accused of murdering Ahmaud Arbery have already come in for harsh judgment from the highest of places. Donald Trump called the slaying of Mr. Arbery, a Black man, “disturbing.” Barack Obama described it as an example of enduring racial injustice. Brian Kemp, Georgia’s Republican governor, called it “absolutely horrific.”

headline.main: In the Trial of Ahmaud Arbery’s Accused Killers, Unsettling Video Will Have a Starring Role
headline.print_headline: Video of Arbery Killing To Have Starring Role In Georgia Murder Trial

docs.abstract: Colinford Mattis and Urooj Rahman expressed regret for the attack on a police car in May 2020. Each could face 10 years in prison.
docs.snippet: Colinford Mattis and Urooj Rahman expressed regret for the attack on a police car in May 2020. Each could face 10 years in prison.
docs.lead_paragraph: On a May night in 2020, two young lawyers — high achievers who had risen from working-class roots to prestigious schools and promising careers — joined thousands of others on the streets of Brooklyn to protest the murder of George Floyd.

headline.main: Brooklyn Lawyers Plead Guilty in Firebomb Case

byline.original: By Rebecca Davis O'Brien and Jonah E. Bromwich

docs.abstract: The abrupt reversals have come in response to rising levels of crime, the exodus of officers and political pressures.
docs.snippet: The abrupt reversals have come in response to rising levels of crime, the exodus of officers and political pressures.
docs.lead_paragraph: DALLAS — The demonstrators came at night, chanting and blowing whistles outside the home of Mayor Eric Johnson, protesting in occasionally personal terms his staunch refusal to cut funding to the Dallas Police Department.

headline.main: A Year After ‘Defund,’ Police Departments Get Their Money Back
headline.print_headline: Cities Reverse On Police Cuts As Crime Rises

docs.abstract: In the city where the “defund the police” movement took off, voters will decide next week whether to replace their Police Department with a new public safety agency.
docs.snippet: In the city where the “defund the police” movement took off, voters will decide next week whether to replace their Police Department with a new public safety agency.
docs.lead_paragraph: MINNEAPOLIS — Days after a police officer murdered George Floyd, protesters gathered outside Mayor Jacob Frey’s home demanding that the Minneapolis Police Department be abolished. The mayor said no. The crowd responded with jeers of “Shame!”

headline.main: Keep or Replace? The Fate of the Minneapolis Police Is in Voters’ Hands.
headline.print_headline: Minneapolis Voters Hold Future Of Police Dept. in Their Hands

byline.original: By Mitch Smith and Tim Arango
